## Missing Data

### Why It Matters

Linear models in R run on **complete cases only** by default. If 20 out of 62 observations have missing values, you effectively lose a large portion of your data — which can bias results or reduce power.

### Visualising Missing Data (VIM package in R)

```r
library(VIM)
aggr(data)              # Bar chart of missing values per variable
barMiss(data[, c("sleep", "exposure")])  # Missing by category
histMiss(data[, c("sleep", "span")])     # Histogram with missingness
marginplot(data[, c("sleep", "span")])   # Scatterplot with marginal boxplots
```

- **Red** in plots = values that are missing.
- **Blue** = values that are present.
- The red boxplot shows the distribution of Y when X is missing (and vice versa).

### Handling Missing Data

| Method | When to use |
|---|---|
| `na.omit()` / `complete.cases()` | Few missing values, no pattern, data is MCAR |
| `irmi()` (VIM) | Continuous variables, iterative regression imputation |
| `mice()` | Multiple imputation using predictive mean matching (PMM); assumes MAR |

**IRMI** (Iterative Robust Model-Based Imputation): Each variable takes a turn as the response; the remaining variables predict its missing values. Repeats until all variables have been imputed.

**MICE** (Multiple Imputation by Chained Equations): Creates **m = 5** (default) imputed datasets, fits the model on each, and **pools** the results. The pooled standard error is always **larger** than for individual datasets because it accounts for imputation uncertainty.

> When to delete vs. impute: If missing data is **Missing Completely At Random (MCAR)** and there are very few missing values, deletion is acceptable. If there is a pattern (MNAR or MAR), imputation is preferred.

